🔷 What is Serialization?

👉 Serialization is the process of converting a Java object into a byte stream so it can be:

Saved to a file
Sent over a network
Stored in a database/cache

👉 Reverse process = Deserialization

🧠 Simple Definition

👉
Serialization = Object → Bytes
Deserialization = Bytes → Object

🔷 How Serialization works in Java

Java provides built-in support via:

ObjectOutputStream → write object
ObjectInputStream → read object

🔷 Marker Interface: Serializable
class User implements Serializable {}

👉 Important:

Serializable is a marker interface
It has no methods
It just tells JVM:
👉 “This class can be serialized”

🔷 What actually gets serialized?

✔ Instance variables
❌ Static variables (class-level)
❌ Transient variables (explicitly ignored)

🔑 Example
class User implements Serializable {
    String name;
    transient String password; // won't be serialized
}

🔷 serialVersionUID (VERY IMPORTANT 🔥)

private static final long serialVersionUID = 1L;

🧠 What is it?

👉 A unique ID for a class version

❗ Why needed?

When deserializing:

JVM checks if class version matches

❌ Without it:

-JVM generates one automatically
-If class changes → mismatch → Exception

⚠️ Exception:

InvalidClassException

✅ Best Practice:

Always define serialVersionUID

🔷 Serialization Process (Internal Flow)

👉 When you serialize an object:

-JVM checks if class implements Serializable
-Converts object into byte stream

Saves:

(i)Class metadata
(ii)Field values

👉 During deserialization:

(i)JVM reads byte stream
(ii)Creates object without constructor
(iii)Restores field values

🔷 Important Concept: Constructor is NOT called

👉 During deserialization:

User u = (User) in.readObject();

👉 Constructor is skipped ❗

🧠 Why?
Object is reconstructed directly from bytes

🔷 Common Issues in Serialization:

❌ 1. NotSerializableException

If object contains non-serializable field:

class A {
    B b; // B not serializable
}

👉 Fix:

-Make B serializable OR
-Mark as transient

❌ 2. Version mismatch

Class changed after serialization

👉 Fix:

Use serialVersionUID

❌ 3. Security Issues
Deserialization can execute malicious code

👉 Important in real-world systems

🔷 Serialization in Spring Boot (Real-world)

Spring Boot rarely uses Java serialization directly.

Instead uses:

JSON (via Jackson)

👉 Example:

@GetMapping("/user")
public User getUser() {
    return new User("Tanisha", 22);
}

👉 Internally:

Object → JSON (serialization)
JSON → Object (deserialization)

🔷 Java Serialization vs JSON Serialization

Feature	                             Java Serialization	                             JSON

Format	                             Binary	                                         Text
Readable	                         ❌	                                              ✔
Language dependent	                 ✔	                                              ❌
Use case	                         Internal	                                      APIs

🔷 Real-life Analogy

Serialization:

Packing object into a box (bytes)

Deserialization:

Unpacking it back into original object

